WEBVTT

00:03.699 --> 00:04.047
.

00:04.091 --> 00:05.875
- Previously on
"New Amsterdam"...

00:05.918 --> 00:07.485
- Somebody reported that you

00:07.529 --> 00:09.270
have a problem with Adderall.

00:09.313 --> 00:11.620
- You're asking me if I've
ever risked a patient's life

00:11.663 --> 00:12.969
because I'm stoned.

00:13.013 --> 00:14.362
- Yeah, and you haven't
answered the question.

00:14.405 --> 00:15.798
- What do you think
would happen

00:15.841 --> 00:18.192
if you stopped helping people?
Who would they see?

00:18.235 --> 00:21.282
- They would see
a corny, nerdy,

00:21.325 --> 00:24.372
fat, worthless nothing.

00:24.415 --> 00:27.070
- All right, since you all
prescribe 79% of our opioids,

00:27.114 --> 00:29.029
I am giving you one year

00:29.072 --> 00:31.509
to prescribe 79% less,

00:31.553 --> 00:34.599
and anyone who doesn't
will be fired.

00:34.643 --> 00:35.905
[dramatic music]

00:35.948 --> 00:38.386
- I think they're clean.

00:39.343 --> 00:41.606
- The damage to his heart
was extensive.

00:41.650 --> 00:44.087
The virus also ravaged
the surrounding heart muscle.

00:44.131 --> 00:45.697
- How bad?

00:45.741 --> 00:47.960
- Even if you found the best
heart surgeon in the world,

00:48.004 --> 00:50.659
I'm not sure it'd be enough.

00:50.702 --> 00:52.226
[Andrew Bird's
"Three White Horses"]

00:52.269 --> 00:55.838
- ♪ There'll be
three white horses ♪

00:55.881 --> 00:58.841
♪ All in a line

00:58.884 --> 01:02.323
♪ There'll be
three white horses ♪

01:02.366 --> 01:04.194
♪ In a line

01:04.238 --> 01:07.197
♪

01:07.241 --> 01:11.158
♪ Three white horses

01:11.201 --> 01:14.509
♪ When you go that way

01:14.552 --> 01:18.426
♪ You will need somebody

01:18.469 --> 01:20.906
♪ When you come to die

01:20.950 --> 01:24.954
♪

01:24.997 --> 01:26.999
♪ Don't dismiss it

01:27.043 --> 01:30.525
♪ Like it's easy

01:30.568 --> 01:34.224
♪ Tell me what's so easy

01:34.268 --> 01:38.098
♪ About coming
to say goodbye? ♪

01:41.144 --> 01:43.364
♪ You're gonna miss her

01:43.407 --> 01:46.932
♪ In the evening

01:46.976 --> 01:48.934
- Hey.
- Yeah?

01:48.978 --> 01:51.241
- Dr. Reynolds.

01:51.285 --> 01:53.809
I used to work here.

01:53.852 --> 01:55.289
- Hospital ID?

01:55.332 --> 01:58.379
- No, but I should be
in the system.

02:01.425 --> 02:02.818
- ♪ There'll be
three white horses ♪

02:02.861 --> 02:04.689
- Oh, thank you.

02:04.733 --> 02:08.650
- ♪ When you go that way

02:08.693 --> 02:12.175
♪ You will need somebody

02:12.219 --> 02:14.830
♪ When you come to die

02:18.094 --> 02:19.965
♪ It's not desperation

02:20.009 --> 02:23.360
♪ That we're breeding

02:23.404 --> 02:26.450
♪ It's just
a need we're feeding ♪

02:26.494 --> 02:30.454
♪ Before you say goodbye

02:33.544 --> 02:35.416
♪ You're gonna miss me

02:35.459 --> 02:39.202
♪ In the evening

02:39.246 --> 02:41.639
- [sighs]

02:41.683 --> 02:44.686
- ♪ Somebody when you
come to die ♪

02:46.688 --> 02:50.431
♪ You know all you need is

02:50.474 --> 02:52.433
♪ Somebody when you

02:52.476 --> 02:54.261
♪ Come to die

02:54.304 --> 02:56.698
- So?

02:56.741 --> 02:59.266
- I can't operate.

02:59.309 --> 03:02.225
[dramatic music]

03:02.269 --> 03:04.314
♪

03:04.358 --> 03:05.489
Here's Vijay's cardiac echo.

03:05.533 --> 03:07.012
- What do you mean
"can't operate"?

03:07.056 --> 03:08.971
- His mitral valve, it's
greater than 60% regurgitation.

03:09.014 --> 03:10.668
That's secondary to a ruptured
papillary muscle.

03:10.712 --> 03:13.018
- I didn't fly you out here
to not operate.

03:13.062 --> 03:14.716
- Listen, his EF is under 20%.

03:14.759 --> 03:16.848
These numbers aren't even
compatible with life.

03:16.892 --> 03:19.024
- Right, which is exactly why
you need to fix the valve.

03:19.068 --> 03:20.722
- I can't fix it
because the virus has damaged

03:20.765 --> 03:22.376
the heart muscle
around the valve.

03:22.419 --> 03:24.378
There's nothing to sew
a new valve into.

03:24.421 --> 03:26.249
- Doing nothing
isn't an option.

03:26.293 --> 03:27.685
- I didn't say
I was doing nothing.

03:27.729 --> 03:29.470
Look, I'm gonna use a catheter.
- TAVR?

03:29.513 --> 03:31.254
- All right,
I'm gonna place a clip...

03:31.298 --> 03:32.734
- A clip?

03:32.777 --> 03:34.605
- Into the mitral's weakened
area--that should fix it.

03:34.649 --> 03:36.738
- He's dying, Floyd.
He needs surgery.

03:36.781 --> 03:39.219
- Okay, look, you brought me
here because of my expertise,

03:39.262 --> 03:40.394
and because you trust me.
[beeper beeping]

03:40.437 --> 03:42.265
Right now my expertise
is saying this.

03:42.309 --> 03:44.833
- I gotta go.

03:44.876 --> 03:47.009
- What happened to
"How can I help?"

03:47.052 --> 03:51.013
- The virus hit us hard.
Nothing's the same.

03:52.319 --> 03:54.190
- My hospital had three.

03:54.234 --> 03:56.410
- Three what?

03:56.453 --> 03:58.716
- Only three deaths.

03:58.760 --> 04:02.024
I feel guilty just saying it.

04:02.067 --> 04:05.245
- Don't.
You were spared.

04:05.288 --> 04:07.377
I wish we were.

04:07.421 --> 04:09.423
Especially Lauren.

04:10.946 --> 04:13.427
It hit her the worst.

04:13.470 --> 04:16.734
[somber music]

04:16.778 --> 04:23.654
♪

04:29.312 --> 04:30.879
[knocking on door]

04:32.576 --> 04:35.187
[knocking continues]

04:35.231 --> 04:37.929
- Candelario's on!
- Dr. Bloom, it's Gladys.

04:37.973 --> 04:41.368
- Get Candelario!
- It's about Iggy.

04:41.411 --> 04:43.283
[dramatic music]

04:43.326 --> 04:46.373
- I'm on my way out.

04:46.416 --> 04:47.896
♪

04:47.939 --> 04:49.680
- He's sweaty,
wobbly on his feet.

04:49.724 --> 04:51.160
- Did he take a COVID test?

04:51.203 --> 04:52.509
- PCR came back negative,

04:52.553 --> 04:54.903
but he can hardly stand.

04:54.946 --> 04:58.820
♪

04:58.863 --> 05:00.648
[knocks]

05:00.691 --> 05:02.650
- Ig?

05:04.347 --> 05:05.740
- Hey.
- Hey.

05:05.783 --> 05:09.134
- What brings you down to the--
Ooh.

05:09.178 --> 05:11.920
- Aw, God, Gladys was right.
You gotta go home.

05:11.963 --> 05:14.357
- No, I just--
I stood up too fast.

05:14.401 --> 05:16.533
I got a head rush.
- You're valor is noted,

05:16.577 --> 05:18.143
but if you've got the flu,
you gotta go.

05:18.187 --> 05:20.537
- I don't have the flu,
I'm just--I'm tired.

05:20.581 --> 05:22.539
- You're color's not great.

05:22.583 --> 05:24.454
- Lauren, if I feel
anything flu-y, I'll, uh...

05:24.498 --> 05:26.064
[sighs]
- Hey.

05:26.108 --> 05:27.457
- I'll page you.
- Hey, hey, hey, hey, hey.

05:27.501 --> 05:28.719
Hey, come on, come on.
Sit down.

05:28.763 --> 05:30.242
Sit down.
- No, no, I'm fine.

05:30.286 --> 05:31.896
I just--I haven't eaten.

05:31.940 --> 05:33.507
- Since when?

05:33.550 --> 05:35.552
- [clears throat]

05:35.596 --> 05:37.859
- Hey.
How many meals?

05:41.079 --> 05:43.038
- [sighs]

05:43.081 --> 05:44.605
- How many days?

05:47.390 --> 05:48.652
- Two.

05:50.437 --> 05:52.526
Maybe three.

05:56.051 --> 05:57.574
- Hi.

05:57.618 --> 06:00.403
I thought you might enjoy
a full-bodied Ethiopian roast,

06:00.447 --> 06:02.318
carefully wrapped
for contactless delivery,

06:02.362 --> 06:04.625
as an apology.
- None needed.

06:04.668 --> 06:08.237
I'll take the coffee,
but keep the apology.

06:08.280 --> 06:10.848
- Um, look, all of this, um,

06:10.892 --> 06:13.808
being close bodies
and trusting, normal,

06:13.851 --> 06:15.157
it's kinda like
I don't remember

06:15.200 --> 06:16.332
how to do any of it anymore.

06:16.376 --> 06:19.030
- I get it,
if that's what it is.

06:19.074 --> 06:21.076
- What do you mean?

06:21.119 --> 06:23.861
- I mean, there's no reason

06:23.905 --> 06:25.950
to force something
that's not there anymore.

06:25.994 --> 06:27.561
- No, it's not--
that's not it.

06:27.604 --> 06:29.389
- Are you sure?

06:29.432 --> 06:32.348
[somber music]

06:32.392 --> 06:33.567
[sighs]

06:33.610 --> 06:35.656
It's okay, Helen.

06:35.699 --> 06:37.614
COVID took away
a lot of things.

06:37.658 --> 06:39.355
We focus here
on the lives lost,

06:39.399 --> 06:42.445
but there were
other casualties.

06:42.489 --> 06:44.665
♪

06:44.708 --> 06:47.102
See you around.

06:47.145 --> 06:49.104
- It's all I know right now.
I'm sorry.

06:49.147 --> 06:50.279
- I know, but Dr. Kapoor

06:50.322 --> 06:51.541
was supposed to be
in the OR hours ago.

06:51.585 --> 06:53.413
So that can't be good, right?

06:53.456 --> 06:54.762
- I know it's hard to wait.

06:54.805 --> 06:57.199
As soon as I have an update,
I will let you know.

06:58.505 --> 07:00.681
- Hi, Ella, I'm Dr. Sharpe,

07:00.724 --> 07:02.422
one of Vijay's colleagues.

07:02.465 --> 07:04.424
- Of course, Double French
Roast with a splash of agave.

07:04.467 --> 07:05.555
- Yep.
[laughs]

07:05.599 --> 07:07.296
- I'm sorry I'm not standing.

07:07.339 --> 07:09.341
I just--I'm worried that
if I get out of this chair,

07:09.385 --> 07:10.908
Vijay's gonna die
during surgery.

07:10.952 --> 07:12.170
I have OCD,

07:12.214 --> 07:14.608
and my irrational thoughts
won this round.

07:14.651 --> 07:16.087
- It happens.

07:16.131 --> 07:18.873
- Ah, I wish it hadn't

07:18.916 --> 07:20.962
because sitting is making
my leg cramps worse.

07:21.005 --> 07:23.443
I stretch, but they just
keep coming back.

07:23.486 --> 07:24.487
- How long has that
been going on?

07:24.531 --> 07:26.794
- Um, an hour or two?

07:26.837 --> 07:29.492
I woke up breathing better
for the first time in months,

07:29.536 --> 07:31.755
but my back gets hot
and now this.

07:31.799 --> 07:33.235
Although my pregnancy podcast

07:33.278 --> 07:35.977
said I was going to start
feeling confident and sexy.

07:36.020 --> 07:38.501
- Ella, it sounds like
you're in labor.

07:38.545 --> 07:41.461
♪

07:41.504 --> 07:42.940
- I got your page.

07:42.984 --> 07:44.551
- We caught the guy
who's been pinching Oxy

07:44.594 --> 07:46.466
from the dispensary.
- An orderly?

07:46.509 --> 07:48.598
- My name is Paul.
- Paul Argento.

07:48.642 --> 07:50.557
Been working here for 13 months

07:50.600 --> 07:52.863
and stealing from you
just as long.

07:52.907 --> 07:54.996
- You mind telling me why?

07:56.214 --> 07:57.694
Look, if we're using,
we can get you tre--

07:57.738 --> 07:59.391
- They're not for me.

07:59.435 --> 08:00.480
- Well, if you're
selling them...

08:00.523 --> 08:03.047
- The--they're for my mom.

08:04.005 --> 08:06.616
She got diagnosed
with osteosarcoma a year ago.

08:06.660 --> 08:08.270
She used to be happy,

08:08.313 --> 08:09.750
but now the pain's killing her.

08:09.793 --> 08:12.492
She can't even walk her dog.

08:12.535 --> 08:14.755
The Oxy was helping,
but that idiot doctor of hers--

08:14.798 --> 08:17.584
- He's been giving me
less and less for my pain.

08:18.628 --> 08:20.717
Told me I had to be weaned off.

08:20.761 --> 08:23.154
- And what is he giving you
as an alternative?

08:23.198 --> 08:24.634
- Nothing.

08:24.678 --> 08:27.158
- That's awful.

08:27.202 --> 08:29.683
Whoever was treating you
stops today.

08:29.726 --> 08:31.989
You're a patient
at New Amsterdam now.

08:32.033 --> 08:34.601
- But my doctor
is at New Amsterdam.

08:34.644 --> 08:36.167
[dramatic music]

08:36.211 --> 08:37.386
- Brenna Argento.

08:37.429 --> 08:39.519
- I know her well.
Stage three bone cancer.

08:39.562 --> 08:42.739
- She can barely walk, and
yet you pulled her Oxy. Why?

08:42.783 --> 08:45.002
- Because received a letter
from a Dr. Max Goodwin

08:45.046 --> 08:46.787
saying that if I didn't,
I'd be fired.

08:46.830 --> 08:49.137
- No, for overprescribing,
needlessly, recklessly,

08:49.180 --> 08:50.965
but Brenna--
- Who wasn't the type

08:51.008 --> 08:52.836
of patient you pictured
when you wrote it.

08:52.880 --> 08:55.056
This is what happens when
you needlessly and recklessly

08:55.099 --> 08:57.798
make a blanket policy without a
regard to individual patients.

08:57.841 --> 09:00.017
- [laughs]
She is suffering.

09:00.061 --> 09:03.194
- Of course she's suffering,
but not because of me.

09:03.238 --> 09:04.631
Because of you.

09:04.674 --> 09:06.720
♪

09:09.157 --> 09:09.374
.

09:09.418 --> 09:13.117
[fast-paced percussive music]

09:13.161 --> 09:15.119
- Don't hang up!

09:15.163 --> 09:17.208
Because I want
whoever that is to know

09:17.252 --> 09:18.514
that I'm person who killed you

09:18.558 --> 09:20.037
for reversing
this hospital's policy

09:20.081 --> 09:21.691
on limiting
opiate prescriptions.

09:22.823 --> 09:25.129
- [cooing]

09:25.173 --> 09:26.740
♪

09:26.783 --> 09:28.350
- I am unmoved.

09:28.393 --> 09:30.744
- Wow, okay, I gotta go.
Yeah, Daddy's in trouble.

09:30.787 --> 09:32.572
Love you.
Bye.

09:32.615 --> 09:36.140
- Opioid prescriptions
at New Amsterdam are down 38%.

09:36.184 --> 09:38.752
We've won awards.
We're a national model.

09:38.795 --> 09:40.884
The Nyler family's
rightfully drowning

09:40.928 --> 09:42.190
in class-action lawsuits.

09:42.233 --> 09:44.366
- And yet,
deaths from narcotic overdoses

09:44.409 --> 09:46.498
are skyrocketing.
Know by how much?

09:46.542 --> 09:49.327
240%.
So mission accomplished?

09:49.371 --> 09:51.547
- You instituted that policy.

09:51.591 --> 09:54.942
- Yeah, to save lives, but that
policy was a blunt instrument

09:54.985 --> 09:56.508
that put paper over people.

09:56.552 --> 09:58.902
- So you're denouncing your own
hugely successful policy?

09:58.946 --> 10:00.512
- Well, that's just it.
It wasn't successful.

10:00.556 --> 10:03.559
Our books were clean, but
at the cost of hurting people

10:03.603 --> 10:05.430
who needed our help.
We have to do better.

10:05.474 --> 10:07.084
- By returning
to the halcyon days

10:07.128 --> 10:09.652
when doled out highly addictive
drugs like Halloween candy?

10:09.696 --> 10:12.176
- Karen, do you know what it
feels like to have bone cancer?

10:12.220 --> 10:13.700
- Oh, Max.
- It's like being stabbed

10:13.743 --> 10:15.310
over and over again

10:15.353 --> 10:17.399
all day long
with a serrated knife,

10:17.442 --> 10:19.270
and the only, the only thing,

10:19.314 --> 10:21.925
that is gonna ease
that excruciating pain

10:21.969 --> 10:23.318
is opioids.

10:23.361 --> 10:25.276
Those aren't my words.

10:25.320 --> 10:26.713
They're Brenna Argento's,

10:26.756 --> 10:29.237
a patient that we...

10:29.280 --> 10:31.543
that I let down.

10:31.587 --> 10:34.329
- You don't convince me
opioids work.

10:34.372 --> 10:37.462
That was never the issue.
This was always about abuse.

10:37.506 --> 10:39.726
About ensuring the drugs
we send into the world

10:39.769 --> 10:42.032
aren't getting our patients
hooked or being sold

10:42.076 --> 10:43.338
or ending up
in the wrong hands.

10:43.381 --> 10:44.731
- You're absolutely right.

10:44.774 --> 10:46.646
- I don't like it
when we're fighting,

10:46.689 --> 10:47.995
and you agree with me.
- No, you're right.

10:48.038 --> 10:50.040
We can get opioids
to the people who need them

10:50.084 --> 10:51.781
and in quantities
that are in safe--

10:51.825 --> 10:53.435
Karen, yes!

10:54.784 --> 10:56.264
- [sighs]

10:56.307 --> 10:57.395
- Sorry, forgot this
was my office.

10:57.439 --> 10:58.962
Uh, would you excuse me?

10:59.006 --> 11:01.573
♪

11:01.617 --> 11:05.186
- Contractions are organized
and four minutes apart.

11:05.229 --> 11:07.275
It's official.

11:07.318 --> 11:08.711
- What's official?

11:08.755 --> 11:11.453
- Ella, you're gonna have
a baby today.

11:11.496 --> 11:13.150
- Oh, no, that's impossible

11:13.194 --> 11:15.326
'cause my due date's
in three weeks.

11:15.370 --> 11:17.720
On a Friday.
And today's Tuesday.

11:17.764 --> 11:20.854
And Dr. Richardson was gonna
delivery my baby.

11:20.897 --> 11:22.029
- Well, looks like someone

11:22.072 --> 11:23.639
wants to crash
this party early.

11:23.683 --> 11:25.989
I'll be covering for
Dr. Richardson all day,

11:26.033 --> 11:28.035
so I think we'll be seeing
a lot of each other.

11:28.078 --> 11:30.777
I'll be back in a bit
to check on your progress.

11:30.820 --> 11:32.779
- Thank you.

11:34.694 --> 11:37.740
- This is not OCD.
This is a relaxation exercise.

11:37.784 --> 11:39.742
- Good, you know, good.
Relaxing is good.

11:39.786 --> 11:41.396
- How is this happening?

11:41.439 --> 11:43.790
I am not ready for this.

11:43.833 --> 11:45.661
- Is there someone that you
would like me to call?

11:45.705 --> 11:48.403
Family, friends?
- No, there's only Vijay,

11:48.446 --> 11:50.144
and he promised
he'd be here for this.

11:50.187 --> 11:52.494
Um, okay, uh...

11:52.537 --> 11:54.975
Who--uh.
You could try my doula,

11:55.018 --> 11:57.151
but I think she's in Portland
this weekend

11:57.194 --> 11:59.675
for her great-aunt's birthday,
so that feels like a dead end.

11:59.719 --> 12:01.764
- I know a great doula here
at New Amsterdam.

12:01.808 --> 12:03.679
- Has she been working with me
for the last 26 weeks

12:03.723 --> 12:06.247
on ways to manage my OCD
for this specific moment?

12:06.290 --> 12:09.293
- Uh, no.

12:09.337 --> 12:11.992
- I had a plan.
I had such a perfect plan.

12:12.035 --> 12:14.255
Oh.

12:14.298 --> 12:16.736
- Surgical suite prep
to OR seven.

12:16.779 --> 12:18.476
- [sighs]

12:18.520 --> 12:21.131
[line trilling]

12:21.175 --> 12:22.393
Uh, Leela, hi.

12:22.437 --> 12:23.655
Can you clear
my afternoon please?

12:23.699 --> 12:25.353
No pagers, no patients.
Nothing.

12:25.396 --> 12:27.529
- What are you doing?

12:27.572 --> 12:29.879
- I'm kicking off a new plan.

12:29.923 --> 12:33.578
♪

12:33.622 --> 12:34.754
- Okay.

12:34.797 --> 12:37.321
Well, your concern
is duly noted,

12:37.365 --> 12:40.455
but I don't need your help.
But thank you.

12:40.498 --> 12:41.935
- You know
your staff's noticed?

12:41.978 --> 12:43.806
I mean, even I can tell
you're weak on your feet,

12:43.850 --> 12:46.461
and you just admitted
to caloric restrictions

12:46.504 --> 12:48.202
spanning over 72 hours.

12:48.245 --> 12:50.073
- It's a cleanse, Lauren.

12:50.117 --> 12:52.336
Really, I'm fine.

12:52.380 --> 12:54.164
- You know you sound like
every first-timer

12:54.208 --> 12:55.687
who's just been
dragged to rehab.

12:55.731 --> 12:57.864
- Whatever it is
that you think this is,

12:57.907 --> 13:00.214
it isn't, and I don't
appreciate the accusation.

13:00.257 --> 13:03.217
- Do you hide food?

13:03.260 --> 13:04.609
- Lauren--

13:04.653 --> 13:06.611
- Sometimes people starve
themselves after a binge,

13:06.655 --> 13:08.483
and not for health reasons,
but because they feel ashamed.

13:08.526 --> 13:09.832
- Well, it's not like that.

13:09.876 --> 13:12.008
- Must be hard to hide
your stash at home

13:12.052 --> 13:14.097
what with Martin and the kids,
so where do you keep it?

13:14.141 --> 13:16.230
- Nowhere, I don't have a--
- Here in this office?

13:16.273 --> 13:18.493
- No.

13:18.536 --> 13:20.451
Lauren, don't.
Don't.

13:24.281 --> 13:26.718
- Oh, Iggy.

13:28.111 --> 13:29.809
- [sighs]

13:31.375 --> 13:32.942
- Hey.
- It's...

13:36.685 --> 13:38.948
- The left atrium's
barely moving.

13:38.992 --> 13:41.124
- COVID really did
a number on his heart.

13:41.168 --> 13:43.997
- Vijay said he got it
here at New Amsterdam?

13:44.040 --> 13:46.826
- He's not the only one.
- Approaching the left atrium.

13:46.869 --> 13:48.392
You too?

13:48.436 --> 13:50.046
- It was in the early days.

13:50.090 --> 13:53.441
I wore the same mask day and
night for two weeks straight.

13:53.484 --> 13:55.617
Then I was intubating
a patient,

13:55.660 --> 13:57.314
got a focused blast
of exhaled air

13:57.358 --> 13:58.620
right in my face.
[laughs]

13:58.663 --> 14:00.709
I just felt the virus
coming through the mask.

14:00.752 --> 14:03.451
Sure enough, three days later,
cough, fever, headaches.

14:03.494 --> 14:06.236
- Yeah.
Vijay.

14:06.280 --> 14:08.238
Why was he even here, you know?

14:08.282 --> 14:11.633
I mean, his age, knowing
the risk, why even come in?

14:11.676 --> 14:13.635
- How could he not?
- Vitals are stable.

14:13.678 --> 14:16.507
- We all felt a sense of duty,

14:16.551 --> 14:18.901
of pride even.

14:23.166 --> 14:24.341
- [sighs]

14:24.385 --> 14:27.127
[no sound]

14:27.170 --> 14:28.563
- What's that?
You can't...

14:28.606 --> 14:30.870
Ah, sorry about that.

14:30.913 --> 14:32.697
Hi, again.

14:32.741 --> 14:36.310
There are quite a few of you
on this call,

14:36.353 --> 14:37.311
and, well, you all have

14:37.354 --> 14:38.312
something in common,

14:38.355 --> 14:39.313
and that's that

14:39.356 --> 14:40.314
you are all victims

14:40.357 --> 14:41.489
of New Amsterdam's

14:41.532 --> 14:43.099
opioid policy
that kept pain meds

14:43.143 --> 14:45.493
from the people
who need them the most.

14:45.536 --> 14:47.103
We failed you

14:47.147 --> 14:49.453
in the most fundamental way

14:49.497 --> 14:51.020
a hospital can.

14:51.064 --> 14:53.414
You came to us in pain,

14:53.457 --> 14:56.547
you asked for our help,
and we said no.

14:56.591 --> 14:58.680
And what's worse,

14:58.723 --> 15:01.552
is we shamed you for asking.

15:01.596 --> 15:03.946
So I'm here to apologize

15:03.990 --> 15:07.471
and to tell you
that that cruel policy

15:07.515 --> 15:09.256
ends now.

15:09.299 --> 15:10.213
[cheers and applause]

15:10.257 --> 15:11.214
- Yes!

15:11.258 --> 15:12.259
- Finally.

15:12.302 --> 15:13.303
- It's about damn time.

15:13.347 --> 15:14.957
- Yeah, all patients will get

15:15.001 --> 15:16.698
the prescribed opioids
they need

15:16.741 --> 15:18.134
based on their pain levels,

15:18.178 --> 15:19.919
and all have you to do
is swing by New Amsterdam

15:19.962 --> 15:22.399
once a week
to pick up your pills.

15:22.443 --> 15:23.966
Easy as pie.

15:24.010 --> 15:25.707
- Wait, what?
- [speaking Spanish]

15:25.750 --> 15:27.100
- I can't do that.
- No, no.

15:27.143 --> 15:29.493
We're gonna make it
very, very simple.

15:29.537 --> 15:31.495
We're gonna establish
a special clinic.

15:31.539 --> 15:33.019
- What the hell's
a special clinic?

15:33.062 --> 15:34.237
- I live in Long Island.

15:34.281 --> 15:36.152
It's a three-hour trip
if I'm lucky.

15:36.196 --> 15:38.154
- Excuse me,
I have four kids and a job,

15:38.198 --> 15:39.721
and you expect me
to spend my one day off

15:39.764 --> 15:40.983
with you every week?

15:41.027 --> 15:43.377
- Okay, I'm hearing
some concerns

15:43.420 --> 15:45.118
about the policy that we were

15:45.161 --> 15:47.250
all just very excited about.

15:47.294 --> 15:48.904
But I'll just be honest.

15:48.948 --> 15:51.124
The hospital has some concerns

15:51.167 --> 15:54.083
about portion control.

15:54.127 --> 15:56.520
- Portion control?
Like I'm five?

15:56.564 --> 15:57.913
- No, no, no.
[laughs]

15:57.957 --> 16:00.220
It's just that these pills
are highly addictive,

16:00.263 --> 16:01.438
and we do need to make sure

16:01.482 --> 16:02.918
that nobody is using

16:02.962 --> 16:05.138
or distributing these pills
inappropriately.

16:05.181 --> 16:06.878
- [laughs]
So now you think I'm dealing?

16:06.922 --> 16:08.358
- No.
- You just said

16:08.402 --> 16:10.230
the shaming of chronic pain
treatment was over.

16:10.273 --> 16:11.927
- And it is, but...

16:11.971 --> 16:14.016
- Are you serious, Max?
- Come on.

16:14.060 --> 16:15.800
- That's not gonna work.
- No way.

16:15.844 --> 16:16.932
- Um...

16:16.976 --> 16:18.890
- What a joke.
- I'm outta here.

16:18.934 --> 16:20.414
- Come on, Max.
- This is ridiculous.

16:20.457 --> 16:22.764
- Thanks for nothing.
- I'm closing this window.

16:22.807 --> 16:25.941
[fast-paced percussive music]

16:25.985 --> 16:27.464
♪

16:30.119 --> 16:30.511
.

16:30.554 --> 16:33.862
- Thank you all for responding
to my multiple app requests.

16:33.905 --> 16:36.212
I have some deliveries for you.

16:36.256 --> 16:39.607
Addresses are grouped together
for maximum efficiency.

16:39.650 --> 16:42.001
- Those burritos?
- They are not.

16:42.044 --> 16:43.741
- Are your items
heat sensitive?

16:43.785 --> 16:46.353
- No, we're good.
So if you wanna grab your bag--

16:46.396 --> 16:48.833
- Are dealing with breakable
items like figurines?

16:48.877 --> 16:51.271
- Are they insured?
- Are we liable here?

16:51.314 --> 16:53.925
- I--no, it's very simple.

16:53.969 --> 16:56.232
Some of our patients
are having a hard time

16:56.276 --> 16:58.495
getting to the hospital
to pick up their prescriptions,

16:58.539 --> 17:01.324
so I am hiring all of you

17:01.368 --> 17:02.543
to solve that problem.

17:02.586 --> 17:04.936
- So we're delivering drugs.

17:04.980 --> 17:06.416
- [laughs]

17:06.460 --> 17:08.114
Technically, yes?

17:09.898 --> 17:12.031
But uh...

17:12.074 --> 17:14.903
did I mention
there's a 25% tip?

17:16.078 --> 17:17.645
- All right.

17:17.688 --> 17:19.951
♪

17:19.995 --> 17:23.042
- Yo, how many
are we allowed to take?

17:23.085 --> 17:25.087
- Okay, okay.

17:25.131 --> 17:26.306
That was smooth.

17:26.349 --> 17:27.742
- That was the alcohol swipe.

17:27.785 --> 17:30.353
- Getting started now.

17:30.397 --> 17:32.442
- Oh, my God.
Distract me.

17:32.486 --> 17:33.748
- Uh, distract you?

17:33.791 --> 17:35.010
- Say something.
Anything.

17:35.054 --> 17:36.620
- Um, okay.

17:36.664 --> 17:39.449
Did you know that women blink
nearly twice as much as men?

17:39.493 --> 17:41.147
- Nope, something interesting.

17:41.190 --> 17:43.584
- Fine, fine.
Okay.

17:43.627 --> 17:45.716
- [gasps]
Aah, it feels like a sword!

17:45.760 --> 17:47.805
Like I'm literally
being stabbed by a sword!

17:47.849 --> 17:49.938
- All right, okay.
Um...

17:49.981 --> 17:52.636
there's this gorgeous man,

17:52.680 --> 17:54.029
this doctor that I was seeing.

17:54.073 --> 17:55.813
- Yes, good.
- Am seeing.

17:55.857 --> 17:58.903
Well, mmm, was seeing.
[stammers] I don't know.

17:58.947 --> 18:00.296
[laughs]
I don't know.

18:00.340 --> 18:03.256
But we started dating
just when the pandemic hit,

18:03.299 --> 18:05.649
and I thought about him
for months during the lockdown.

18:05.693 --> 18:07.521
I fantasized about him.

18:07.564 --> 18:09.827
But then, the other day,

18:09.871 --> 18:12.265
when he reached out
to touch me, I pulled away.

18:13.875 --> 18:17.052
I recoiled like I was
physically repelled by him...

18:19.446 --> 18:20.621
And I don't know.
I don't know.

18:20.664 --> 18:21.839
Is it me?

18:21.883 --> 18:23.319
Am I that scared
to be touched by someone,

18:23.363 --> 18:25.669
or is it him?

18:27.367 --> 18:28.759
Did what we have,

18:28.803 --> 18:31.153
did it just sort of...

18:32.372 --> 18:33.503
- No, keep going.

18:33.547 --> 18:35.288
But fast forward
to the interesting part.

18:35.331 --> 18:38.508
Did he dump you?
Are you sad?

18:38.552 --> 18:40.815
[gasps]
Aah!

18:40.858 --> 18:42.773
- Was that a contraction?

18:42.817 --> 18:43.861
- Mm-hmm.
Mmm!

18:43.905 --> 18:45.298
- What?
The epidural seems to be

18:45.341 --> 18:46.995
taking its sweet time.
- Yeah, it should've

18:47.038 --> 18:49.171
kicked in by now.
Unfortunately,

18:49.215 --> 18:52.131
I think the catheter's tip
is in the sub-dural space.

18:52.174 --> 18:53.654
- It didn't work?

18:53.697 --> 18:55.917
- It didn't work?
[sighs]

18:55.960 --> 18:58.789
Uh, can we try again
the epidural?

18:58.833 --> 19:00.965
[dramatic music]

19:01.009 --> 19:03.968
- It's too late, sweetheart.
You're too far along.

19:04.012 --> 19:06.493
Ella, you're gonna
have to do this

19:06.536 --> 19:08.234
on your own.

19:08.277 --> 19:10.323
- No.
No.

19:10.366 --> 19:11.933
No, no, no, no, no, no.

19:13.064 --> 19:15.719
- All right,
I know how this looks.

19:15.763 --> 19:19.419
I do.
Believe me.

19:19.462 --> 19:22.204
But these are my dad's words.

19:22.248 --> 19:24.163
They're his words,

19:24.206 --> 19:25.381
and growing up,

19:25.425 --> 19:28.210
I had to hear them
practically every day.

19:28.254 --> 19:31.866
My father struggled with
his weight his entire life,

19:31.909 --> 19:34.347
and he didn't want me
to suffer the same fate.

19:34.390 --> 19:36.087
So at an early age,

19:36.131 --> 19:38.525
he took an interest
in my weight.

19:38.568 --> 19:39.830
- An interest?

19:39.874 --> 19:41.484
- Mm-hmm, yeah.

19:41.528 --> 19:43.921
It started around
the third grade.

19:43.965 --> 19:46.750
I filled out a little bit,
and, uh,

19:46.794 --> 19:49.405
he would make me go
on crash diets

19:49.449 --> 19:51.364
out of the blue,

19:51.407 --> 19:53.844
skip meals, take meal
replacement bars to school.

19:53.888 --> 19:55.237
- As a nine-year-old?

19:55.281 --> 19:57.413
- Mm-hmm.

19:57.457 --> 20:00.024
Yeah, and...

20:00.068 --> 20:03.767
he would make me
take my shirt off

20:03.811 --> 20:05.987
so he could take pictures
of my body

20:06.030 --> 20:09.382
to, um, put up on the wall
in the basement

20:09.425 --> 20:11.949
next to the makeshift gym
that he'd built for me

20:11.993 --> 20:13.821
to track my process.

20:13.864 --> 20:17.172
There was
a body progress chart.

20:17.216 --> 20:19.609
And if I would ever
walk by him,

20:19.653 --> 20:21.045
he would smack my gut and say,

20:21.089 --> 20:22.569
"Jesus, look at that thing."

20:22.612 --> 20:24.266
[somber music]

20:24.310 --> 20:26.573
"Got a lot of work left to do,
don't we, buddy?"

20:26.616 --> 20:29.053
And what's worse is,

20:29.097 --> 20:32.231
if I ever had a good weigh-in,
which was not very often,

20:32.274 --> 20:35.277
I, uh,
I would be over the moon

20:35.321 --> 20:37.366
because it would make me
feel loved.

20:37.410 --> 20:41.631
♪

20:41.675 --> 20:43.981
[sighs]

20:44.025 --> 20:47.463
Then...this one time,

20:47.507 --> 20:49.552
I guess I would've been
in middle school by this point,

20:49.596 --> 20:51.641
I just--I--

20:51.685 --> 20:53.295
I hated everything
about myself.

20:55.166 --> 20:57.604
So I tried to hang myself.

20:57.647 --> 20:59.388
- What?

20:59.432 --> 21:01.042
Jesus, Iggy.

21:01.085 --> 21:03.392
- No, it's okay.
[cries]

21:03.436 --> 21:06.830
It didn't work, obviously.

21:06.874 --> 21:08.658
Ironically, I was too fat

21:08.702 --> 21:10.312
for the rod
in the basement closet

21:10.356 --> 21:13.315
to hold me up,
and it crashed down on my head,

21:13.359 --> 21:16.100
and my mom heard the sound
and came to help me.

21:16.144 --> 21:18.799
- What?
What did your dad say?

21:18.842 --> 21:20.496
- Oh.

21:20.540 --> 21:23.586
My dad, um, well,

21:23.630 --> 21:25.066
that night at my weigh-in,

21:25.109 --> 21:27.416
he just snapped
another polaroid for the wall

21:27.460 --> 21:29.723
and acted like nothing
ever happened.

21:30.637 --> 21:32.029
- [scoffs]

21:32.073 --> 21:34.162
- That's my dad for you.

21:39.385 --> 21:40.908
- [sighs]

21:42.605 --> 21:44.868
These are his words,

21:44.912 --> 21:46.566
but they don't control me
anymore.

21:46.609 --> 21:48.219
They do not.

21:48.263 --> 21:49.743
They serve as a reminder
of all of the things

21:49.786 --> 21:52.093
that I have conquered,
which is a lot,

21:52.136 --> 21:54.225
and sometimes
I look at these words,

21:54.269 --> 21:56.880
and they remind that
I'm not that kid anymore

21:56.924 --> 21:58.795
and that I'm making
better decisions.

21:58.839 --> 22:01.276
I'm making healthy decisions
in my life.

22:03.713 --> 22:07.587
And that I no longer need to
stand around with my shirt off

22:07.630 --> 22:10.329
and let others judge me.
- What?

22:11.547 --> 22:13.723
You know that's not
what I was doing, right?

22:13.767 --> 22:15.899
- I'm fine.

22:15.943 --> 22:17.727
I am more than fine.

22:17.771 --> 22:19.250
You can rest easy.

22:19.294 --> 22:22.863
Now if you'll excuse me,
I have patients to see.

22:23.951 --> 22:25.126
[door clicks open]

22:25.169 --> 22:27.563
- No, I'm--I'm being careful.

22:27.607 --> 22:29.870
Yeah.

22:29.913 --> 22:32.351
Ma, I'm gonna see you soon.

22:32.394 --> 22:35.266
Okay, yeah.
I love you too.

22:35.310 --> 22:37.051
All right.

22:37.094 --> 22:39.488
- Heard you pulled off
one hell of a TAVR.

22:39.532 --> 22:41.272
Just this side of genius.

22:41.316 --> 22:43.231
- I accept your apology, Max.

22:43.274 --> 22:44.406
- You need anything else
while you're here?

22:44.450 --> 22:46.408
- Aw, no, just catching up
with some folks.

22:46.452 --> 22:49.019
You know, I missed my favorite
scrub nurse in OR today, JJ.

22:49.063 --> 22:50.194
- Devlin.
- Yeah.

22:50.238 --> 22:51.544
- He passed away
a few months ago.

22:51.587 --> 22:52.980
COVID.

22:54.068 --> 22:55.765
- [sighs]
That's too bad.

22:55.809 --> 22:57.419
- Everything's changed.

22:57.463 --> 22:59.290
- Dr. Max Goodwin.
- That's me.

22:59.334 --> 23:01.728
- You're under arrest.
- Whoa, what's going on?

23:01.771 --> 23:03.077
- For what?

23:03.120 --> 23:04.557
- For writing
700 Oxycodone prescriptions,

23:04.600 --> 23:06.254
each one over 100 milligrams,

23:06.297 --> 23:07.777
and distributing them
with bike messengers.

23:07.821 --> 23:09.605
- Oh, that.

23:09.649 --> 23:11.738
- It's nice to see some things
haven't changed.

23:11.781 --> 23:14.349
[beeper beeping]

23:14.393 --> 23:18.440
[fast-paced dramatic music]

23:18.484 --> 23:19.267
- BP's 80/40 and falling.

23:19.310 --> 23:20.442
- Push epi, I'm coming in.

23:20.486 --> 23:22.401
I need an echo over here.

23:22.444 --> 23:23.750
- What happened?

23:23.793 --> 23:26.492
- The clip didn't hold.
His heart is failing.

23:26.535 --> 23:31.192
♪

23:33.107 --> 23:33.324
.

23:33.368 --> 23:34.717
- [sighs]

23:34.761 --> 23:38.112
[fast-paced percussive music]

23:38.155 --> 23:39.461
- The DA only agreed

23:39.505 --> 23:41.463
to not press charges
for narcotics trafficking

23:41.507 --> 23:42.812
because
you're an essential worker.

23:42.856 --> 23:44.988
- Huh.
- Congratulations.

23:45.032 --> 23:47.034
You're one of the select few
to benefit from COVID-19.

23:47.077 --> 23:48.383
- Thanks for getting me out.

23:48.427 --> 23:49.993
- I have half a mind
to leave you in there.

23:50.037 --> 23:51.952
- You know, pharmacies
mail opioids all the time.

23:51.995 --> 23:54.520
Bike messengers
are almost the same.

23:54.563 --> 23:56.652
- I wonder if you've ever
considered how exhausting it is

23:56.696 --> 23:57.784
to be your boss.

23:57.827 --> 23:59.873
All your wonderful ideas

23:59.916 --> 24:00.917
that come with such chaos,

24:00.961 --> 24:02.658
every single one.

24:02.702 --> 24:04.399
[sighs]
It's funny.

24:04.443 --> 24:06.836
The thing you're best at is the
part of my job I hate the most.

24:06.880 --> 24:08.795
You ignore reality.
- That's not fair.

24:08.838 --> 24:11.841
- Says the man who just
sent 70,000 milligrams of Oxy

24:11.885 --> 24:13.408
out into the street
via bike messenger.

24:13.452 --> 24:15.323
I know it seems
like a good idea.

24:15.366 --> 24:17.499
Hell, it might even be
a good idea,

24:17.543 --> 24:19.980
but it's my job to deal
with the reality of your ideas,

24:20.023 --> 24:22.548
in this case criminal reality.
Optics matter.

24:22.591 --> 24:24.593
- Patients matter.

24:24.637 --> 24:27.422
- I'm glad you're
helping people, Max, truly.

24:27.466 --> 24:30.077
But your plan
has no accountability.

24:30.120 --> 24:31.513
You don't know where
these drugs are going.

24:31.557 --> 24:32.949
You just don't.

24:32.993 --> 24:35.996
And opioids,
the potential for abuse,

24:36.039 --> 24:38.607
it's a very emotional issue.

24:38.651 --> 24:41.523
To many people,
opioids aren't pain medicine.

24:41.567 --> 24:43.525
They're what killed
someone they loved.

24:43.569 --> 24:46.528
[somber music]

24:46.572 --> 24:48.269
♪

24:48.312 --> 24:50.053
- [sighs]

24:50.967 --> 24:52.969
- Wait.
Iggy.

24:53.013 --> 24:54.667
Iggy, I wasn't judging you.

24:54.710 --> 24:56.059
- You could've fooled me.

24:56.103 --> 24:58.845
- It was just--people die
from what you're doing.

24:58.888 --> 25:00.194
- What did she say?
[chatter]

25:00.237 --> 25:01.848
[murmuring continues]

25:01.891 --> 25:06.156
[dramatic music]

25:06.200 --> 25:09.290
- In here.
In here.

25:14.643 --> 25:16.340
- Ig.
- [sighs]

25:16.384 --> 25:18.560
- Ig, look, I'm sorry
for making a scene.

25:18.604 --> 25:20.083
- You should be.

25:20.127 --> 25:22.129
- It's just

25:22.172 --> 25:25.132
I've seen people in my ED
with eating disorders.

25:25.175 --> 25:27.047
I mean, I've known people
with eating disorders.

25:27.090 --> 25:28.788
- [sighs]
- Some of them...

25:28.831 --> 25:29.919
they're not here anymore.

25:29.963 --> 25:31.355
- Mm-hmm.

25:31.399 --> 25:33.140
- Look.

25:33.183 --> 25:35.577
I know as well anyone

25:35.621 --> 25:38.232
that the truth
is really difficult.

25:38.275 --> 25:41.409
- I'm sorry.
What are you doing?

25:41.452 --> 25:43.977
Are you comparing your issues
to mine right now?

25:44.020 --> 25:45.631
Let me just mirror
that back for you

25:45.674 --> 25:47.067
so you can hear it out loud.

25:47.110 --> 25:49.548
I'm on the Jimmy Kimmel diet,

25:49.591 --> 25:52.551
and you almost killed a patient
because you are a drug addict.

25:54.553 --> 25:57.120
Not the same.
- That was way out of line.

25:57.164 --> 25:59.166
- I'm outta line?
It's not hard, Lauren.

25:59.209 --> 26:00.471
This is a hospital.

26:00.515 --> 26:02.082
There's only one line
that matters.

26:02.125 --> 26:04.911
You were hurting patients.
I am not.

26:04.954 --> 26:06.390
Plain and simple!

26:06.434 --> 26:08.262
- Patients aren't
the only people you can hurt.

26:08.305 --> 26:09.916
- Oh, yeah?
Well, I think the janitors

26:09.959 --> 26:11.613
are safe from my eating too.
- Yeah?

26:11.657 --> 26:13.615
What about your kids?

26:14.442 --> 26:16.096
- Excuse me?
- You're starving yourself.

26:16.139 --> 26:17.576
You think
they don't notice that?

26:17.619 --> 26:18.751
- You stop talking.
- How many meals have you

26:18.794 --> 26:19.882
had with them where you

26:19.926 --> 26:21.101
haven't eaten anything?
- Stop!

26:21.144 --> 26:22.276
- How many have
you skipped altogether?

26:22.319 --> 26:23.625
I mean, what kind
of screwed up issues

26:23.669 --> 26:25.192
are your kids gonna have
with food because of you?

26:25.235 --> 26:27.194
[knocking]
Occupied!

26:29.675 --> 26:31.633
- It's a bad time, Gladys.

26:31.677 --> 26:33.809
- It's Dr. Kapoor.

26:33.853 --> 26:35.158
- The clip failed,

26:35.202 --> 26:37.117
tore right through
the valve leaflets.

26:37.160 --> 26:38.379
I'm gonna have to crack open
his chest

26:38.422 --> 26:39.859
and put in an artificial valve.

26:39.902 --> 26:41.643
- That's a big surgery.

26:41.687 --> 26:43.776
- I thought you said you
couldn't sew into the muscle.

26:43.819 --> 26:46.648
What changed?
- Nothing. Not a damn thing.

26:46.692 --> 26:49.520
- But he'll make it through
the surgery, right?

26:49.564 --> 26:52.480
[somber music]

26:52.523 --> 26:54.830
♪

26:54.874 --> 26:56.310
- That's why I thought
you should see him now,

26:56.353 --> 26:59.487
and have one more moment
with him

26:59.530 --> 27:01.663
in case...

27:01.707 --> 27:03.186
I'm gonna go prep.

27:03.230 --> 27:10.367
♪

27:11.064 --> 27:13.370
- [grunts]

27:13.414 --> 27:14.458
[sighs]

27:14.502 --> 27:16.373
- You're fully effaced
and dilated,

27:16.417 --> 27:18.637
but the baby's still
at minus three position.

27:18.680 --> 27:20.813
Ella, the delivery isn't
progressing as I had hoped.

27:20.856 --> 27:22.423
- What does that mean?

27:22.466 --> 27:25.078
- When your contraction comes,
you need to push real hard.

27:25.121 --> 27:26.993
- Oh, my God,
this is a disaster.

27:27.036 --> 27:29.343
- Maybe you
could hold her hand.

27:29.386 --> 27:32.651
- [heavy breathing]
- E-Ella.

27:32.694 --> 27:33.564
Look.
Look.

27:33.608 --> 27:35.349
Count them out with me, okay?

27:35.392 --> 27:37.046
- [groans]
- Here we go.

27:37.090 --> 27:38.700
Give me
the biggest push you got.

27:38.744 --> 27:40.615
- You can do this.
Come on, come on.

27:40.659 --> 27:43.879
- No, I can't!
Stop, I don't want to!

27:43.923 --> 27:46.882
What if the baby's not okay?
What if I hurt it?

27:46.926 --> 27:49.711
What I ate undercooked meat
and didn't know it?

27:49.755 --> 27:51.539
And seven weeks ago
I took a bath

27:51.582 --> 27:52.801
right after the tub
was cleaned,

27:52.845 --> 27:54.020
and the water
probably had bleach in it.

27:54.063 --> 27:55.282
What kind of mom
is that careless?

27:55.325 --> 27:56.892
- You are not careless.

27:56.936 --> 27:59.242
You have disorder that sends
your pregnancy into overdrive,

27:59.286 --> 28:01.549
but you fought it,
and you've made it this far.

28:01.592 --> 28:03.899
- I cheated.
I got scans all the time.

28:03.943 --> 28:05.292
Sometimes two days in a row

28:05.335 --> 28:06.859
in case something happened
while I was sleeping.

28:06.902 --> 28:08.512
But then everything shut down,

28:08.556 --> 28:10.340
and Vijay got sick,
and I don't know why,

28:10.384 --> 28:12.081
but I just convinced myself

28:12.125 --> 28:14.736
that the baby was going to be
okay as long as he was okay.

28:14.780 --> 28:16.042
What if Vijay's not okay?

28:16.085 --> 28:18.305
- Ella!
Everything on that monitor

28:18.348 --> 28:19.915
says that your baby
is going to be okay,

28:19.959 --> 28:21.177
but you have to deliver it...

28:21.221 --> 28:23.136
- No!
Oh.

28:23.179 --> 28:24.093
- Contractions peaking.
- Aah!

28:24.137 --> 28:25.399
- You can do it.

28:25.442 --> 28:26.748
Your baby needs you
to push now.

28:26.792 --> 28:29.577
- [grunts]
Aah.

28:30.883 --> 28:33.102
[crying]

28:35.888 --> 28:38.804
[crying]

28:45.811 --> 28:47.464
- Eh?

28:48.204 --> 28:50.467
- Yeah, yeah, buddy?
What is it?

28:51.817 --> 28:53.340
Hit me.

28:54.123 --> 28:56.865
- You're such a good dad.

28:56.909 --> 28:58.475
- Aw, I don't know.
I...

29:05.134 --> 29:07.789
- If this doesn't work out...

29:10.096 --> 29:12.794
Will you look after

29:12.838 --> 29:15.188
Ella and the baby?

29:18.017 --> 29:21.150
- [crying]

29:49.918 --> 29:51.964
- You've got this.

29:52.007 --> 29:53.879
You can do it.

29:55.184 --> 29:56.969
- Hey.

29:57.012 --> 29:58.361
And I am dying...

29:58.405 --> 29:59.841
- What are you talking about?
Don't be silly.

29:59.885 --> 30:01.234
You are going
to be annoying her

30:01.277 --> 30:02.844
for the rest of your life,
okay?

30:04.890 --> 30:06.717
- Please.

30:09.372 --> 30:12.985
- If something happens, I...

30:13.028 --> 30:15.161
[cries]
Yes.

30:15.204 --> 30:17.337
Obviously.

30:18.904 --> 30:19.861
- Good.

30:19.905 --> 30:21.732
- [sighs]

30:33.005 --> 30:33.396
.

30:33.440 --> 30:35.746
[somber music]

30:35.790 --> 30:38.053
- Listen, Iggy.

30:38.097 --> 30:39.881
- Lauren, I'm fine.
- No.

30:39.925 --> 30:42.231
I never should've dragged
your kids into this.

30:43.929 --> 30:45.887
I'm really sorry.

30:48.237 --> 30:51.371
- A couple nights ago,
I was, uh,

30:51.414 --> 30:53.155
I was wearing
this nice new sweater

30:53.199 --> 30:54.853
that Martin gave me,
and, um...

30:58.465 --> 31:00.684
Harper told me that
I looked handsome in it.

31:02.861 --> 31:05.559
Then I immediately grabbed
my stomach,

31:05.602 --> 31:07.430
and I told her
that she was wrong.

31:10.042 --> 31:11.739
It just popped out of mouth.

31:11.782 --> 31:13.741
[crying]

31:17.310 --> 31:19.616
I say things like that
all the time.

31:22.271 --> 31:24.143
And Vijay thinks
that I'm a great father?

31:24.186 --> 31:25.361
[crying]

31:25.405 --> 31:27.233
I'm teaching my kids

31:27.276 --> 31:30.453
that someone who looks like me
doesn't deserve to be loved.

31:33.065 --> 31:36.807
That is the same lesson
that my dad taught me.

31:36.851 --> 31:38.809
Aw, man.

31:40.289 --> 31:43.466
He just used different words.

31:46.992 --> 31:48.297
- Iggy.

31:50.256 --> 31:52.954
These aren't your dad's words.

31:52.998 --> 31:54.216
You wrote this.

31:54.260 --> 31:55.783
- I know.

31:55.826 --> 31:59.439
- These are your words.
You're calling yourself this,

31:59.482 --> 32:03.008
and you're keep suffering
until you stop.

32:03.051 --> 32:05.967
- [sighs]
If I can't stop,

32:06.011 --> 32:09.492
this note, that voice...

32:11.581 --> 32:14.497
It's the thing about myself
that feels the most true.

32:15.585 --> 32:18.893
How do you stop believing that?

32:19.894 --> 32:23.115
- Well, you could try
talking to a therapist.

32:23.158 --> 32:24.812
- [crying]

32:26.945 --> 32:28.033
- Hey, I did.

32:30.035 --> 32:31.688
He saved my life.

32:38.826 --> 32:40.219
- [sighs]

32:40.262 --> 32:42.003
- Come here.

32:44.397 --> 32:47.313
- Thank you.
- Yeah.

32:47.356 --> 32:51.752
- ♪ Even if we try

32:51.795 --> 32:56.670
♪ Even if we try

32:56.713 --> 32:59.412
♪ To make ourselves

32:59.455 --> 33:02.371
♪ All right

33:02.415 --> 33:06.854
♪ To mend our severed lives

33:06.897 --> 33:08.334
[no audio]

33:08.377 --> 33:12.555
♪ While all the rivers rage

33:12.599 --> 33:17.386
♪ Descend upon the sage

33:17.430 --> 33:22.000
♪ Alone on willowed eves

33:22.043 --> 33:26.656
